# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] In software engineering, **CI/CD** or **CICD** is the combined practices of continuous integration (CI) and continuous delivery (CD) or, less often, continuous deployment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] They are sometimes referred to collectively as continuous development or continuous software development.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] Producing software in short cycles with high speed and frequency so that reliable software can be released at any time, with a simple and repeatable deployment process when deciding to deploy.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] Automatic rollout of new software functionality.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] When these three processes occur in order, they may be described as a "CI/CD pipeline".
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] CI/CD bridges the gaps between development and operation activities and teams by enforcing automation in building, testing and deployment of applications.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] CI/CD services compile the incremental code changes made by developers, then link and package them into software deliverables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] Automated tests verify the software functionality, and automated deployment services deliver them to end users.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] The aim is to increase early defect discovery, increase productivity, and provide faster release cycles.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] The process contrasts with traditional methods where a collection of software updates were integrated into one large batch before deploying the newer version.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] of software applications throughout its development life cycle.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-cd] The CI/CD practice, or *CI/CD pipeline*, forms the backbone of modern day DevOps operations.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] CI/CD pipelines are the fundamental component of GitLab CI/CD.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipelines are configured in a `.gitlab-ci.yml` file by using YAML keywords.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipelines can run automatically for specific events, like when pushing to a branch, creating a merge request, or on a schedule.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When needed, you can also run pipelines manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] To get started with your first pipeline, see Create and run your first GitLab CI/CD pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipelines and their component jobs and stages are defined with YAML keywords in the CI/CD pipeline configuration file for each project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When editing CI/CD configuration in GitLab, you should use the pipeline editor.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] If you use VS Code to edit your GitLab CI/CD configuration, the GitLab for VS Code extension helps you validate your configuration and view your pipeline status.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipelines can be manually executed, with predefined or manually-specified variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You might do this if the results of a pipeline (for example, a code build) are required outside the standard operation of the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In the left sidebar, select **Build** > **Pipelines**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In the **Run for branch name or tag** field, select the branch or tag to run the pipeline for.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The pipeline now executes the jobs as configured.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can see all variables that are specified when the pipeline runs manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When you turn on this setting, users with the Developer role can view variable values that might contain sensitive information from any manual pipeline run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] For sensitive data like credentials or tokens, use protected variables or external secrets management instead of manual pipeline variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In the left sidebar, select **Settings** > **CI/CD**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Go to **Build** > **Pipelines** and select a pipeline that was run manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] If you have the Developer, Maintainer, or Owner role, you can select the eye icon to reveal values.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can use the `description` and `value` keywords to define pipeline-level (global) variables that are prefilled when running a pipeline manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Use the description to explain information such as what the variable is used for, and what the acceptable values are.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can use Markdown in the description.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Job-level variables cannot be pre-filled.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In manually-triggered pipelines, the **New pipeline** page displays all pipeline-level variables that have a `description` defined in the `.gitlab-ci.yml` file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The description displays below the variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can change the prefilled value, which overrides the value for that single pipeline run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Any variables overridden by using this process are expanded and not masked.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] If you do not define a `value` for the variable in the configuration file, the variable name is still listed, but the value field is blank.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Because of a known issue, projects that use compliance pipelines can have prefilled variables not appear when running a pipeline manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] To workaround this issue, change the compliance pipeline configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can define an array of CI/CD variable values the user can select from when running a pipeline manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] These values are in a dropdown list in the **New pipeline** page.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Add the list of value options to `options` and set the default value with `value`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The string in `value` must also be included in the `options` list.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can use a query string to pre-populate the **New pipeline** page.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] For each `var` or `file_var`, a key and value are required.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Manual jobs, allow you to require manual interaction before moving forward in the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can do this straight from the pipeline graph.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select **Run** ( ) to execute that particular job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] For example, your pipeline can start automatically, but require a manual action to deploy to production.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] (Pipeline graph that shows four stages: build, test, canary, and production.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] If a stage contains only manual jobs, you can start all the jobs at the same time by selecting **Run all manual** ( ) above the stage.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] If the stage contains non-manual jobs, the option is not displayed.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] To push a commit without triggering a pipeline, add `[ci skip]` or `[skip ci]`, using any capitalization, to your commit message.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Alternatively, with Git 2.10 or later, use the `ci.skip` Git push option.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The `ci.skip` push option does not skip merge request pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipeline execution policies and scan execution policies can restrict or disable the `[skip ci]` directive.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select either the pipeline ID (for example `#123456789`) or the pipeline status icon (for example **Passed**) of the pipeline to delete.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In the upper right of the pipeline details page, select **Delete**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Deleting a pipeline does not automatically delete its child pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Deleting a pipeline expires all pipeline caches, and deletes all immediately related objects, such as jobs, logs, artifacts, and triggers.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] A strict security model is enforced when pipelines are executed on protected branches.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Review how access to protected variables and runners work in the context of Merge request pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Review the deployment safety page for additional security recommendations for securing your pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can set up your project to automatically trigger a pipeline based on tags in a different project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When a new tag pipeline in the subscribed project finishes, it triggers a pipeline on your project’s default branch, regardless of the tag pipeline’s success, failure, or cancellation.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] As an alternative, you can use CI/CD jobs with pipeline trigger tokens to trigger pipelines when another pipeline runs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] This method is more reliable and flexible than pipeline subscriptions and is the recommended approach.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Enter the project you want to subscribe to, in the format `<namespace>/<project>`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] For example, if the project is `https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab`, use `gitlab-org/gitlab`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The maximum number of upstream pipeline subscriptions is 2 by default, for both the upstream and downstream projects.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] On GitLab Self-Managed, an administrator can change this limit.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] That means that if a job is retried or manually re-run, only the duration of the latest run is included in the total running time.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Because A is retried, it is ignored, and only job A’ is counted.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select **Pipeline ID** in the dropdown list in the upper right to display the pipeline IDs (unique ID across the instance).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select **pipeline IID** to display the pipeline IIDs (internal ID, unique across the project only).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] To view the pipelines that relate to a specific merge request, go to the **Pipelines** tab in the merge request.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select a pipeline to open the pipeline details page which shows every job in the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] From this page you can cancel a running pipeline, retry failed jobs, or delete a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When you configure jobs with the `needs` keyword, you have two options for how to group the jobs in the pipeline details page.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] To group the jobs by `needs` configuration, select **Job dependencies**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can optionally select **Show dependencies** to render lines between dependent jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Jobs in the leftmost column run first, and jobs that depend on them are grouped in the next columns.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipeline mini graphs take less space and can tell you at a quick glance if all jobs passed or something failed.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] They show all related jobs for a single commit and the net result of each stage of your pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You can quickly see what failed and fix it.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The pipeline mini graph always group jobs by stage, and display throughout GitLab when displaying pipeline or commit details.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Stages in pipeline mini graphs are expandable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Hover your mouse over each stage to see the name and status, and select a stage to expand its jobs list.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When a pipeline contains a job that triggers a downstream pipeline, you can see the downstream pipeline in the pipeline details view and mini graphs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In the pipeline details view, a card displays for every triggered downstream pipeline on the right of the pipeline graph.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Hover over a card to see which job triggered the downstream pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select a card to display the downstream pipeline to the right of the pipeline graph.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] In the pipeline mini graph, the status of every triggered downstream pipeline displays as additional status icons to the right of the mini graph.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Select a downstream pipeline status icon to go to the detail page of that downstream pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipeline analytics are available on the **CI/CD Analytics** page.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] Pipeline status and test coverage report badges are available and configurable for each project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] For information on adding pipeline badges to projects, see Pipeline badges.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When a runner picks a pipeline job, GitLab provides that job’s metadata.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] This includes the Git refspecs, which indicate which ref (such as branch or tag) and commit (SHA1) are checked out from your project repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] The refs `refs/heads/<name>` and `refs/tags/<name>` exist in your project repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] GitLab generates the special ref `refs/pipelines/<id>` during a running pipeline job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] This ref can be created even after the associated branch or tag has been deleted.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] It’s therefore useful in some features such as automatically stopping an environment, and merge trains that might run pipelines after branch deletion.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] When a user deletes their GitLab.com account, the deletion does not occur for seven days.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] During this period, any pipeline subscriptions created by that user continue to run with the user’s original permissions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] To prevent unauthorized pipeline executions, immediately update pipeline subscription settings for the deleted user.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] If the predefined variables for a pipeline are defined in a separate file, they might not display in the **New Pipeline** page.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-pipelines] You must have permission to access the separate file, or else the predefined variables cannot be displayed.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] This tutorial shows you how to configure and run your first CI/CD pipeline in GitLab.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] If you are already familiar with basic CI/CD concepts, you can learn about common keywords in Tutorial: Create a complex pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] If you don’t have a project, you can create a public project for free on https://gitlab.com.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] Create a `.gitlab-ci.yml` file at the root of your repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] This file is where you define the CI/CD jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] When you commit the file to your repository, the runner runs your jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] The job results are displayed in a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] In GitLab, runners are agents that run your CI/CD jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] If you’re using GitLab.com, you can skip this step.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] GitLab.com provides instance runners for you.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] As long as you have at least one runner that’s active, with a green circle next to it, you have a runner available to process your jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] If you don’t have access to these settings, contact your GitLab administrator.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] When your CI/CD jobs run, in a later step, they will run on your local machine.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] It is a YAML file where you specify instructions for GitLab CI/CD.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] In the left sidebar, select **Code** > **Repository**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] Above the file list, select the branch you want to commit to.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] If you’re not sure, leave `master` or `main`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] The comments listed in the `echo` commands are displayed in the UI when you view the jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] The values for the predefined variables `$GITLAB_USER_LOGIN` and `$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH` are populated when the jobs run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] The pipeline starts and runs the jobs you defined in the `.gitlab-ci.yml` file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] Now take a look at your pipeline and the jobs within.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] View details of a job by selecting the job name.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] You have successfully created your first CI/CD pipeline in GitLab.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] Now you can get started customizing your `.gitlab-ci.yml` and defining more advanced jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] Here are some tips to get started working with the `.gitlab-ci.yml` file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-quick-start] For the complete `.gitlab-ci.yml` syntax, see the full CI/CD YAML syntax reference.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] This document lists the configuration options for the GitLab `.gitlab-ci.yml` file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] This file is where you define the CI/CD jobs that make up your pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When you are editing your `.gitlab-ci.yml` file, you can validate it with the CI Lint tool.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] GitLab CI/CD configuration uses YAML formatting, so the order of keywords is not important unless otherwise specified.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use CI/CD expressions for more dynamic pipeline configuration options.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] These keywords control pipeline behavior or import additional pipeline configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can set global defaults for some keywords.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Each default keyword is copied to every job that doesn’t already have it defined.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Default configuration does not merge with job configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If the job already has a keyword defined, the job keyword takes precedence and the default configuration for that keyword is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include` to include external YAML files in your CI/CD configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can split one long `.gitlab-ci.yml` file into multiple files to increase readability, or reduce duplication of the same configuration in multiple places.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can also store template files in a central repository and include them in projects.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] The time limit to resolve all files is 30 seconds.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include:component` to add a CI/CD component to the pipeline configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include:local` to include a file that is in the same repository and branch as the configuration file containing the `include` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include:local` instead of symbolic links.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] To include files from another private project on the same GitLab instance, use `include:project` and `include:file`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include:remote` with a full URL to include a file from a different location.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include:template` to include `.gitlab-ci.yml` templates.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `include:inputs` to set the values for input parameters when the included configuration uses `spec:inputs` and is added to the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can use `rules` with `include` to conditionally include other configuration files.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `integrity` with `include:remote` to specify a SHA256 hash of the included remote file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If `integrity` does not match the actual content, the remote file is not processed and the pipeline fails.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `cache` with `include:remote` to cache the fetched remote file content and reduce HTTP requests.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When enabled, the remote file is cached for a specified time-to-live (TTL), improving pipeline performance for configurations that use the same remote includes repeatedly.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Consider the trade-off between performance and freshness when setting cache durations.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Longer cache durations improve performance but might use stale content if the remote file changes frequently.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When `cache` is not defined, the remote file is fetched every time.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `stages` to define stages that contain groups of jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `stage` in a job to configure the job to run in a specific stage.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If a pipeline contains only jobs in the `.pre` or `.post` stages, it does not run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] There must be at least one other job in a different stage.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If all jobs in `build` succeed, the `test` jobs execute in parallel.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If all jobs in `test` succeed, the `deploy` jobs execute in parallel.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If all jobs in `deploy` succeed, the pipeline is marked as `passed`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If any job fails, the pipeline is marked as `failed` and jobs in later stages do not start.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Jobs in the current stage are not stopped and continue to run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `workflow` to control pipeline behavior.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can use some predefined CI/CD variables in `workflow` configuration, but not variables that are only defined when jobs start.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `workflow:auto_cancel:on_new_commit` to configure the behavior of the auto-cancel redundant pipelines feature.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `workflow:auto_cancel:on_job_failure` to configure which jobs should be canceled as soon as one job fails.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] In this example, if `job2` fails, `job1` is canceled if it is still running and `job3` does not start.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can use `name` in `workflow:` to define a name for pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] All pipelines are assigned the defined name.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Any leading or trailing spaces in the name are removed.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] The `rules` keyword in `workflow` is similar to `rules` defined in jobs, but controls whether or not a whole pipeline is created.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When no rules evaluate to true, the pipeline does not run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can use `variables` in `workflow:rules` to define variables for specific pipeline conditions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When the condition matches, the variable is created and can be used by all jobs in the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] If the variable is already defined at the top level as a default variable, the `workflow` variable takes precedence and overrides the default variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `workflow:rules:auto_cancel` to configure the behavior of the `workflow:auto_cancel:on_new_commit` or the `workflow:auto_cancel:on_job_failure` features.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] In this example, `workflow:auto_cancel:on_new_commit` is set to `interruptible` and `workflow:auto_cancel:on_job_failure` is set to `all` for all jobs by default.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] But if a pipeline runs for a protected branch, the rule overrides the default with `on_new_commit: none` and `on_job_failure: none`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Some keywords must be defined in a header section of a YAML configuration file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] The header must be at the top of the file, separated from the rest of the configuration with `---`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Add a `spec` section to the header of a YAML file to configure the behavior of a pipeline when a configuration is added to the pipeline with the `include` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Specs must be declared at the top of a configuration file, in a header section separated from the rest of the configuration with `---`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can use `spec:inputs` to define inputs for the CI/CD configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use the interpolation format `$[[ inputs.input-id ]]` to reference the values outside of the header section.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Inputs are evaluated and interpolated when the configuration is fetched during pipeline creation.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When using `inputs`, interpolation completes before the configuration is merged with the contents of the `.gitlab-ci.yml` file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Inputs are mandatory when included, unless you set a default value with `spec:inputs:default`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `default: ''` to have no default value.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `description` to give a description to a specific input.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] The description does not affect the behavior of the input and is only used to help users of the file understand the input.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Inputs can use `options` to specify a list of allowed values for an input.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `spec:inputs:regex` to specify a regular expression that the input must match.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] In this example, inputs of `v1.0` or `v1.2.3` match the regular expression and pass validation.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] An input of `v1.A.B` does not match the regular expression and fails validation.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `spec:inputs:rules` to define conditional `options` and `default` values for an input based on the values of other inputs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] In this example, when `environment` is `development`, users can only select `small` or `medium` instances.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] When `environment` is `production`, only `large` or `xlarge` instances are available.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `spec:inputs:type` to set a different required type for inputs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `spec:include` to include external input definitions from other files.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] You can share and reuse input definitions across multiple pipeline configurations.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `spec:component` to define which component context data is available for interpolation in a CI/CD component.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Component context provides metadata about the component itself, such as its name, version, and the commit SHA.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] This allows component templates to reference their own metadata dynamically.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use the interpolation format `$[[ component.field-name ]]` to reference component context values in the component template.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] Use `spec:description` to provide a short description of the component.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p01] The description is displayed in the CI/CD Catalog on the component details page, above the inputs table.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The following topics explain how to use keywords to configure CI/CD pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `after_script` to define an array of commands to run last, after a job’s `before_script` and `script` sections complete.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Job configuration and default configuration does not merge together.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the pipeline has `default:after_script` defined, and the job also has `after_script`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Scripts you specify in `after_script` execute in a new shell, separate from any `before_script` or `script` commands.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] `after_script` commands execute before cache and artifact upload operations.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] For more information, see job execution flow.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `allow_failure` to determine whether a pipeline should continue running when a job fails.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When jobs are allowed to fail (`allow_failure: true`) an orange warning ( ) indicates that a job failed.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] However, the pipeline is successful and the associated commit is marked as passed with no warnings.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `allow_failure:exit_codes` to control when a job should be allowed to fail.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The job is `allow_failure: true` for any of the listed exit codes, and `allow_failure` false for any other exit code.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts` to specify which files to save as job artifacts.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Job artifacts are a list of files and directories that are attached to the job when it succeeds, fails, or always.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The artifacts are sent to GitLab after the job finishes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] They are available for download in the GitLab UI if the size is smaller than the maximum artifact size.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] By default, jobs in later stages automatically download all the artifacts created by jobs in earlier stages.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can control artifact download behavior in jobs with `dependencies`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When using the `needs` keyword, jobs can only download artifacts from the jobs defined in the `needs` configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Job artifacts are only collected for successful jobs by default, and artifacts are restored after caches.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the pipeline has `default:artifacts` defined, and the job also has `artifacts`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Paths are relative to the project directory (`$CI_PROJECT_DIR`) and can’t directly link outside it.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This example creates an artifact with `.config` and all the files in the `binaries` directory.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts:exclude` to prevent files from being added to an artifacts archive.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This example stores all files in `binaries/`, but not `*.o` files located in subdirectories of `binaries/`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `expire_in` to specify how long job artifacts are stored before they expire and are deleted.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] After their expiry, artifacts are deleted hourly by default (using a cron job), and are not accessible anymore.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `artifacts:expose_as` keyword to expose artifacts in the merge request UI.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `artifacts:name` keyword to define the name of the created artifacts archive.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can specify a unique name for every archive.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If not defined, the default name is `artifacts`, which becomes `artifacts.zip` when downloaded.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] `artifacts:public` is now superseded by `artifacts:access` which has more options.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts:public` to control whether job artifacts in public pipelines are available for download with the GitLab UI and API by anonymous users, or Guest and Reporter roles.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This option only affects GitLab UI and API access.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] CI/CD jobs using job tokens could still access artifacts with the runner API, regardless of this setting.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To restrict job token access, configure your project’s CI/CD visibility settings to **Only project members**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts:access` to determine who can access the job artifacts from the GitLab UI or API.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This option does not prevent you from forwarding artifacts to downstream pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You cannot use `artifacts:public` and `artifacts:access` in the same job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts:reports` to collect artifacts generated by included templates in jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts:untracked` to add all Git untracked files as artifacts (along with the paths defined in `artifacts:paths`).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] `artifacts:untracked` ignores configuration in the repository’s `.gitignore`, so matching artifacts in `.gitignore` are included.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts:when` to upload artifacts on job failure or despite the failure.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `before_script` to define an array of commands that should run before each job’s `script` commands, but after artifacts are restored.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache` to specify a list of files and directories to cache between jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can only use paths that are in the local working copy.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the pipeline has `default:cache` defined, and the job also has `cache`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] For more information about caches, see Caching in GitLab CI/CD.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Using `cache` at the top level, but not in the `default` section, is deprecated.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `cache:paths` keyword to choose which files or directories to cache.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `cache:key` keyword to give each cache a unique identifying key.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] All jobs that use the same cache key use the same cache, including in different pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If not set, the default key is `default`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] All jobs with the `cache` keyword but no `cache:key` share the `default` cache.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Must be used with `cache: paths`, or nothing is cached.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache:key:files` to generate a new cache key when the content of the specified files change.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the content remains unchanged, the cache key remains consistent across branches and pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can reuse caches and rebuild them less often, which speeds up subsequent pipeline runs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This example creates a cache for Ruby and Node.js dependencies.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The cache is tied to the current versions of the `Gemfile.lock` and `package.json` files.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When one of these files changes, a new cache key is computed and a new cache is created.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Any future job runs that use the same `Gemfile.lock` and `package.json` with `cache:key:files` use the new cache, instead of rebuilding the dependencies.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache:key:files_commits` to generate a new cache key when the latest commit changes for the specified files.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] `cache:key:files_commits` cache keys change whenever the specified files have a new commit, even if the file content remains identical.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This example creates a cache based on the commit history of `package.json` and `yarn.lock`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the commit history changes for these files, a new cache key is computed and a new cache is created.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache:key:prefix` to combine a prefix with the SHA computed for `cache:key:files`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] For example, adding a `prefix` of `$CI_JOB_NAME` causes the key to look like `rspec-feef9576d21ee9b6a32e30c5c79d0a0ceb68d1e5`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If a branch changes `Gemfile.lock`, that branch has a new SHA checksum for `cache:key:files`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] A new cache key is generated, and a new cache is created for that key.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If `Gemfile.lock` is not found, the prefix is added to `default`, so the key in the example would be `rspec-default`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `untracked: true` to cache all files that are untracked in your Git repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache:unprotect` to set a cache to be shared between protected and unprotected branches.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When set to `true`, users without access to protected branches can read and write to cache keys used by protected branches.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache:when` to define when to save the cache, based on the status of the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This example stores the cache whether or not the job fails or succeeds.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To change the upload and download behavior of a cache, use the `cache:policy` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] By default, the job downloads the cache when the job starts, and uploads changes to the cache when the job ends.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This caching style is the `pull-push` policy (default).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To set a job to only download the cache when the job starts, but never upload changes when the job finishes, use `cache:policy:pull`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To set a job to only upload a cache when the job finishes, but never download the cache when the job starts, use `cache:policy:push`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `pull` policy when you have many jobs executing in parallel that use the same cache.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This policy speeds up job execution and reduces load on the cache server.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can use a job with the `push` policy to build the cache.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `cache:fallback_keys` to specify a list of keys to try to restore cache from if there is no cache found for the `cache:key`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Caches are retrieved in the order specified in the `fallback_keys` section.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `coverage` with a custom regular expression to configure how code coverage is extracted from the job output.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] GitLab displays the matched percentage in the MR widget, pipeline job list, and analytics graphs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] GitLab then checks the matched fragment against `\d+(?:\.\d+)?` to extract the number.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `dast_configuration` keyword to specify a site profile and scanner profile to be used in a CI/CD configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Both profiles must first have been created in the project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, the `dast` job extends the `dast` configuration added with the `include` keyword to select a specific site profile and scanner profile.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `dependencies` keyword to define a list of specific jobs to fetch artifacts from.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The specified jobs must all be in earlier stages.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can also set a job to download no artifacts at all.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When `dependencies` is not defined in a job, all jobs in earlier stages are considered dependent and the job fetches all artifacts from those jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To fetch artifacts from a job in the same stage, you must use `needs:artifacts`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You should not combine `dependencies` with `needs` in the same job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, two jobs have artifacts: `build mac` and `build linux`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When `test mac` is executed, the artifacts from `build mac` are downloaded and extracted in the context of the build.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The same thing happens for `test linux` and artifacts from `build linux`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `deploy` job downloads artifacts from all previous jobs because of the stage precedence.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `environment` to define the environment that a job deploys to.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Common environment names are `qa`, `staging`, and `production`, but you can use any name.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Closing (stopping) environments can be achieved with the `on_stop` keyword defined under `environment`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] It declares a different job that runs to close the environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `action` keyword to specify how the job interacts with the environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `auto_stop_in` keyword specifies the lifetime of the environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When an environment expires, GitLab automatically stops it.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When the environment for `review_app` is created, the environment’s lifetime is set to `1 day`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Every time the review app is deployed, that lifetime is also reset to `1 day`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `auto_stop_in` keyword can be used for all environment actions except `stop`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Some actions can be used to reset the scheduled stop time for the environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] For more information, see Access an environment for preparation or verification purposes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `kubernetes` keyword to configure the dashboard for Kubernetes and GitLab-managed Kubernetes resources for an environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use the `deployment_tier` keyword to specify the tier of the deployment environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use CI/CD variables to dynamically name environments.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `deploy as review app` job is marked as a deployment to dynamically create the `review/$CI_COMMIT_REF_SLUG` environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] `$CI_COMMIT_REF_SLUG` is a CI/CD variable set by the runner.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `$CI_ENVIRONMENT_SLUG` variable is based on the environment name, but suitable for inclusion in URLs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the `deploy as review app` job runs in a branch named `pow`, this environment would be accessible with a URL like `https://review-pow.example.com/`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The common use case is to create dynamic environments for branches and use them as review apps.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can see an example that uses review apps at https://gitlab.com/gitlab-examples/review-apps-nginx/.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `extends` to reuse configuration sections.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] It’s an alternative to YAML anchors and is a little more flexible and readable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, the `rspec` job uses the configuration from the `.tests` template job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `hooks` to specify lists of commands to execute on the runner at certain stages of job execution, like before retrieving the Git repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the pipeline has `default:hooks` defined, and the job also has `hooks`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `hooks:pre_get_sources_script` to specify a list of commands to execute on the runner before cloning the Git repository and any submodules.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `identity` to authenticate with third party services using identity federation.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `id_tokens` to create ID tokens to authenticate with third party services.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] All JWTs created this way support OIDC authentication.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The required `aud` sub-keyword is used to configure the `aud` claim for the JWT.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the pipeline has `default:id_tokens` defined, and the job also has `id_tokens`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `image` to specify a Docker image that the job runs in.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the pipeline has `default:image` defined, and the job also has `image`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, the `ruby:3.0` image is the default for all jobs in the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `rspec 2.7` job does not use the default, because it overrides the default with a job-specific `image` section.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The name of the Docker image that the job runs in.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Command or script to execute as the container’s entry point.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When the Docker container is created, the `entrypoint` is translated to the Docker `--entrypoint` option.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The syntax is similar to the Dockerfile `ENTRYPOINT` directive, where each shell token is a separate string in the array.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `image:docker` to pass options to runners using the Docker executor or the Kubernetes executor.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] This keyword does not work with other executor types.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `image:kubernetes` to pass options to the GitLab Runner Kubernetes executor.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The pull policy that the runner uses to fetch the Docker image.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `inputs` to define typed and validated inputs for a job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Job inputs can be overridden when manually running or retrying a job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Job inputs are parameters that provide type safety and validation.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Unlike CI/CD variables, only inputs explicitly defined in the job can be specified when running or retrying the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Reference job input values with the `${{ job.inputs.INPUT_NAME }}` Moa expression syntax.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] All job inputs must have a default value defined with `default`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `type` to define the data type of the input value.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `description` to provide information about the input’s purpose.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The description does not affect the input’s behavior.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `options` to specify a list of allowed values for an input.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The input value must match one of the listed options exactly (case-sensitive).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Validation fails if the value does not match an option.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `regex` to specify a regular expression pattern that the input value must match.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Validation fails if the value does not match the regular expression.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, an input value of `v1.1.1` passes the regex validation, but an input of `v1.1.1-beta` does not.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `inherit` to control inheritance of default keywords and variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `inherit:default` to control the inheritance of default keywords.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `inherit:variables` to control the inheritance of default variables keywords.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `interruptible` to configure the auto-cancel redundant pipelines feature to cancel a job before it completes if a new pipeline on the same ref starts for a newer commit.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If the feature is disabled, the keyword has no effect.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The new pipeline must be for a commit with new changes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] For example, the **Auto-cancel redundant pipelines** feature has no effect if you select **New pipeline** in the UI to run a pipeline for the same commit.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The behavior of the **Auto-cancel redundant pipelines** feature can be controlled by the `workflow:auto_cancel:on_new_commit` setting.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, a new pipeline causes a running pipeline to cancel `step-1` and `step-3` if they are running or pending.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `needs` to execute jobs out-of-order.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Relationships between jobs that use `needs` can be visualized as a directed acyclic graph.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can ignore stage ordering and run some jobs without waiting for others to complete.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Jobs in multiple stages can run concurrently.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] When a job uses `needs`, it no longer downloads all artifacts from previous stages by default, because jobs with `needs` can start before earlier stages complete.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] With `needs` you can only download artifacts from the jobs listed in the `needs` configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `artifacts: true` (default) or `artifacts: false` to control when artifacts are downloaded in jobs that use `needs`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `needs:project` to download artifacts from up to five jobs in other pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The artifacts are downloaded from the latest successful specified job for the specified ref.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To specify multiple jobs, add each as separate array items under the `needs` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If there is a pipeline running for the ref, a job with `needs:project` does not wait for the pipeline to complete.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Instead, the artifacts are downloaded from the latest successful run of the specified job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] `needs:project` must be used with `job`, `ref`, and `artifacts`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, `build_job` downloads the artifacts from the latest successful `build-1` and `build-2` jobs on the `main` branches in the `group/project-name` and `group/project-name-2` projects.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] A child pipeline can download artifacts from a successfully finished job in its parent pipeline or another child pipeline in the same parent-child pipeline hierarchy.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] In this example, the `create-artifact` job in the parent pipeline creates some artifacts.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `child-pipeline` job triggers a child pipeline, and passes the `CI_PIPELINE_ID` variable to the child pipeline as a new `PARENT_PIPELINE_ID` variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The child pipeline can use that variable in `needs:pipeline` to download artifacts from the parent pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Having the `create-artifact` and `child-pipeline` jobs in subsequent stages ensures that the `use-artifact` job only executes when `create-artifact` has successfully finished.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] To need a job that sometimes does not exist in the pipeline, add `optional: true` to the `needs` configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] If not defined, `optional: false` is the default.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Jobs that use `rules`, `only`, or `except` and that are added with `include` might not always be added to a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] You can mirror the pipeline status from an upstream pipeline to a job by using the `needs:pipeline` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The latest pipeline status from the default branch is replicated to the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Jobs can use `parallel:matrix` to run a job multiple times in parallel in a single pipeline, but with different variable values for each instance of the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] Use `needs:parallel:matrix` to execute jobs out-of-order depending on parallelized jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p02] The `linux:rspec` job runs as soon as the `linux:build: [aws, app1]` job finishes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `pages` to define a GitLab Pages job that uploads static content to GitLab.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The content is then published as a website.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] This example renames the `my-html-content/` directory to `public/`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] This directory is exported as an artifact and published with GitLab Pages.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] This example does not move the directory, but uses the `publish` property directly.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] It also configures the pages deployment to be unpublished after a week.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `pages.publish` to configure the content directory of a `pages` job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] This example uses Eleventy to generate a static website and output the generated HTML files into a the `dist/` directory.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] It is also possible to use variables in the `pages.publish` field.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The publish path specified must be relative to the build root.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `pages.path_prefix` to configure a path prefix for parallel deployments of GitLab Pages.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The given value is converted to lowercase and shortened to 63 bytes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Everything except alphanumeric characters or periods is replaced with a hyphen.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Leading and trailing hyphens or periods are not permitted.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, a different pages deployment is created for each branch.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `expire_in` to specify how long a deployment should be available before it expires.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] After the deployment is expired, it’s deactivated by a cron job running every 10 minutes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] By default, parallel deployments expire automatically after 24 hours.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] To disable this behavior, set the value to `never`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `parallel` to run a job multiple times in parallel in a single pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Multiple runners must exist, or a single runner must be configured to run multiple jobs concurrently.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Parallel jobs are named sequentially from `job_name 1/N` to `job_name N/N`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] This example creates 5 jobs that run in parallel, named `test 1/5` to `test 5/5`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `parallel:matrix` to run a job multiple times in parallel in a single pipeline, but with different variable values for each instance of the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The release job must have access to the `glab` CLI, which must be in the `$PATH`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If you use the Shell executor or similar, install `glab` CLI on the server where the runner is registered.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If the tag does not exist in the project yet, it is created at the same time as the release.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] New tags use the SHA associated with the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] To create a release and a new tag at the same time, your `rules` should not configure the job to run only for new tags.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If the tag does not exist, the newly created tag is annotated with the message specified by `tag_message`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If omitted, a lightweight tag is created.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If omitted, it is populated with the value of `release: tag_name`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The `ref` for the release, if the `release: tag_name` doesn’t exist yet.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The title of each milestone the release is associated with.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The date and time when the release is ready.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `release:assets:links` to include asset links in the release.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `resource_group` to create a resource group that ensures a job is mutually exclusive across different pipelines for the same project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] For example, if multiple jobs that belong to the same resource group are queued simultaneously, only one of the jobs starts.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The other jobs wait until the `resource_group` is free.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Resource groups behave similar to semaphores in other programming languages.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] You can choose a process mode to strategically control the job concurrency for your deployment preferences.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The default process mode is `unordered`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] To change the process mode of a resource group, use the API to send a request to edit an existing resource group.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] You can define multiple resource groups per environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] For example, when deploying to physical devices, you might have multiple physical devices.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Each device can be deployed to, but only one deployment can occur per device at any given time.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, two `deploy-to-production` jobs in two separate pipelines can never run at the same time.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] As a result, you can ensure that concurrent deployments never happen to the production environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `retry` to configure how many times a job is retried if it fails.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If not defined, defaults to `0` and jobs do not retry.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] When a job fails, the job is processed up to two more times, until it succeeds or reaches the maximum number of retries.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] By default, all failure types cause the job to be retried.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `retry:when` or `retry:exit_codes` to select which failures to retry on.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `test_advanced` will be retried up to 2 times if the exit code is `137` or if it had a runner system failure.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `retry:when` with `retry:max` to retry jobs for only specific failure cases.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `retry:max` is the maximum number of retries, like `retry`, and can be `0`, `1`, or `2`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If there is a failure other than a runner system failure, the job is not retried.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `retry:exit_codes` with `retry:max` to retry jobs for only specific failure cases.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] You can specify the number of retry attempts for certain stages of job execution using variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules` to include or exclude jobs in pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Rules are evaluated when the pipeline is created, and evaluated in order.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] When a match is found, no more rules are checked and the job is either included or excluded from the pipeline depending on the configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If no rules match, the job is not added to the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] You can combine multiple keywords together for complex rules.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] For additional examples, see Specify when jobs run with `rules`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:changes` to specify when to add a job to a pipeline by checking for changes to specific files.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] For new branch pipelines or when there is no Git `push` event, `rules: changes` always evaluates to true and the job always runs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Pipelines like tag pipelines, scheduled pipelines, and manual pipelines, all do not have a Git `push` event associated with them.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] To cover these cases, use `rules: changes: compare_to` to specify the branch to compare against the pipeline ref.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If you do not use `compare_to`, you should use `rules: changes` only with branch pipelines or merge request pipelines, though `rules: changes` still evaluates to true when creating a new branch.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:changes` to specify that a job only be added to a pipeline when specific files are changed, and use `rules:changes:paths` to specify the files.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `rules:changes:paths` is the same as using `rules:changes` without any subkeys.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] All additional details and related topics are the same.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, both jobs have the same behavior.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:changes:compare_to` to specify which ref to compare against for changes to the files listed under `rules:changes:paths`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, the `docker build` job is only included when the `Dockerfile` has changed relative to `refs/heads/branch1` and the pipeline source is a merge request event.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:changes:regexp` to match changed file paths using a Ruby regular expression instead of glob patterns.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `regexp:` and `paths:` are mutually exclusive.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use exactly one per `rules:changes` block.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Variables in the pattern are expanded before the pattern is matched.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The 255-character limit also applies to the expanded pattern.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, `backend-tests` runs when at least one changed file is outside the `docs/` directory.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `exists` to run a job when certain files or directories exist in the repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `rules:exists:paths` is the same as using `rules:exists` without any subkeys.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:exists:project` to specify the location in which to search for the files listed under `rules:exists:paths`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, the `docker build` job is only included when the `Dockerfile` exists in the project `my-group/my-project` on the commit tagged with `v1.0.0`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:exists:regexp` to match file paths in the repository using a Ruby regular expression instead of glob patterns.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use exactly one per `rules:exists` block.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] In this example, the job runs if any `.go` file exists anywhere in the repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `rules:when` alone or as part of another rule to control conditions for adding a job to a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `rules:when` is similar to `when`, but with slightly different input options.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If a `rules:when` rule is not combined with `if`, `changes`, or `exists`, it always matches if reached when evaluating a job’s rules.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `allow_failure: true` in `rules` to allow a job to fail without stopping the pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] You can also use `allow_failure: true` with a manual job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] The pipeline continues running without waiting for the result of the manual job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] `allow_failure: false` combined with `when: manual` in rules causes the pipeline to wait for the manual job to run before continuing.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] If the rule matches, then the job is a manual job with `allow_failure: true`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `needs` in rules to update a job’s `needs` for specific conditions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] When a condition matches a rule, the job’s `needs` configuration is completely replaced with the `needs` in the rule.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `variables` in `rules` to define variables for specific conditions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p03] Use `interruptible` in rules to update a job’s `interruptible` value for specific conditions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] This feature is available for testing, but not ready for production use.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `run` to define a series of steps to be executed in a job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Each step can be either a script or a predefined step.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You can also provide optional environment variables and inputs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Each array entry must have a `name`, and one `script` or `step` (but not both).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `script` to specify commands for the runner to execute.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] All jobs except trigger jobs require a `script` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `secrets:vault` to specify secrets provided by a HashiCorp Vault.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `secrets:gcp_secret_manager` to specify secrets provided by GCP Secret Manager.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `secrets:gitlab_secrets_manager` to specify secrets from the GitLab Secrets Manager.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `secrets:azure_key_vault` to specify secrets provided by a Azure Key Vault.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] By default, the secret is passed to the job as a `file` type CI/CD variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The value of the secret is stored in the file and the variable contains the path to the file.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If your software can’t use `file` type CI/CD variables, set `file: false` to store the secret value directly in the variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `secrets:token` to explicitly select a token to use when authenticating with the external secrets provider by referencing the token’s CI/CD variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `services` to specify any additional Docker images that your scripts require to run successfully.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The `services` image is linked to the image specified in the `image` keyword.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If the pipeline has `default:services` defined, and the job also has `services`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] To enable inter-service networking, set `FF_NETWORK_PER_BUILD` to `true`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Without this flag, services may not work properly.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] CI/CD variables are supported, but not for `alias`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] To customize `alias` dynamically, use CI/CD inputs instead.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The full name of the image to use for the service.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Additional aliases to access the service from the job’s container.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `services:docker` to pass options to the Docker executor of a GitLab Runner.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `services:kubernetes` to pass options to the GitLab Runner Kubernetes executor.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] A command or script to execute as the container’s entrypoint.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Command or script that should be used as the container’s command.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] It’s translated to arguments passed to Docker after the image’s name.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The syntax is similar to the Dockerfile `CMD` directive, where each shell token is a separate string in the array.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Additional environment variables that are passed exclusively to the service.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Service variables are passed exclusively to the service container and are not available to the job container.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The syntax is the same as job variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `stage` to define which stage a job runs in.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Jobs in the same `stage` can execute in parallel (see **Additional details**).
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If `stage` is not defined, the job uses the `test` stage by default.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use the `.pre` stage to make a job run at the start of a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] By default, `.pre` is the first stage in a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] User-defined stages execute after `.pre`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You do not have to define `.pre` in `stages`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use the `.post` stage to make a job run at the end of a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] By default, `.post` is the last stage in a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] User-defined stages execute before `.post`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You do not have to define `.post` in `stages`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `tags` to select a specific runner from the list of all runners that are available for the project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] When you register a runner, you can specify the runner’s tags, for example `ruby`, `postgres`, or `development`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] To pick up and run a job, a runner must be assigned every tag listed in the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If the pipeline has `default:tags` defined, and the job also has `tags`, the job configuration takes precedence and the default configuration is not used.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] In this example, only runners with both the `ruby` and `postgres` tags can run the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `timeout` to configure a timeout for a specific job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If the job runs for longer than the timeout, the job fails.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The job-level timeout can be longer than the project-level timeout, but can’t be longer than the runner’s timeout.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Trigger jobs can use only a limited set of GitLab CI/CD configuration keywords.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:inputs` to set the inputs for a multi-project pipeline when the downstream pipeline configuration uses `spec:inputs`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:include` to declare that a job is a “trigger job” which starts a child pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:include:inputs` to set the inputs for a child pipeline when the downstream pipeline configuration uses `spec:inputs`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:project` to declare that a job is a “trigger job” which starts a multi-project pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] By default, the multi-project pipeline triggers for the default branch.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:branch` to specify a different branch.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:strategy` to force the `trigger` job to wait for the downstream pipeline to complete before it is marked as **success**.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] This behavior is different than the default, which is for the `trigger` job to be marked as **success** as soon as the downstream pipeline is created.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] This setting makes your pipeline execution linear rather than parallel.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] In this example, jobs from subsequent stages wait for the triggered pipeline to successfully complete before starting.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `trigger:forward` to specify what to forward to the downstream pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You can control what is forwarded to both parent-child pipelines and multi-project pipelines.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Forwarded variables do not get forwarded again in nested downstream pipelines by default, unless the nested downstream trigger job also uses `trigger:forward`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `when` to configure the conditions for when jobs run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If not defined in a job, the default value is `when: on_success`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Always executes `cleanup_job` as the last step in pipeline regardless of success or failure.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Executes `deploy_job` when you run it manually in the GitLab UI.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `manual_confirmation` with `when: manual` to define a custom confirmation message for manual jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If no manual job is defined with `when: manual`, this keyword has no effect.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Manual confirmation works with all manual jobs, including environment stop jobs that use `environment:action: stop`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `start_in` to delay the execution of a job for a specified duration after the job is created.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You must configure `when: delayed` for the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] In this example, the `deploy_production` job starts 30 minutes after the previous stage completes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `variables` to define CI/CD variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Variables can be defined in a CI/CD job, or as a top-level (global) keyword to define default CI/CD variables for all jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You can use job variables in commands in the job’s `script`, `before_script`, or `after_script` sections, and also with some job keywords.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Check the **Supported values** section of each job keyword to see if it supports variables.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] You cannot use job variables as values for global keywords like `include`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Variables defined in a top-level `variables` section act as default variables for all jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Each default variable is made available to every job in the pipeline, except when the job already has a variable defined with the same name.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The variable defined in the job takes precedence, so the value of the default variable with the same name cannot be used in the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Like job variables, you cannot use default variables as values for other global keywords, like `include`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use the `description` keyword to define a description for a default variable.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] The description displays with the prefilled variable name when running a pipeline manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use the `value` keyword to define a pipeline-level (default) variable’s value.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] When used with `variables: description`, the variable value is prefilled when running a pipeline manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use `variables:options` to define an array of values that are selectable in the UI when running a pipeline manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] If there is no `description`, this keyword has no effect.
[src:gitlab-ci/ci-yaml-p04] Use the `expand` keyword to configure a variable to be expandable or not.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:gitlab-ci/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] CI/CD is a continuous method of software development, where you continuously build, test, deploy, and monitor iterative code changes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] This iterative process helps reduce the chance that you develop new code based on buggy or failed previous versions.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] GitLab CI/CD can catch bugs early in the development cycle, and help ensure that the code deployed to production complies with your established code standards.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] To use GitLab CI/CD, you start with a `.gitlab-ci.yml` file at the root of your project.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] This file specifies the stages, jobs, and scripts to be executed during your CI/CD pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] It is a YAML file with its own custom syntax.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] The filename must be `.gitlab-ci.yml` and is case-sensitive, but you can configure a different filename.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] In this file, you define variables, dependencies between jobs, and specify when and how each job should be executed.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] A pipeline is defined in the `.gitlab-ci.yml` file, and executes when the file runs on a runner.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] Pipelines can be triggered by various events, like commits or merges, or can be on schedule.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] In your pipeline, you can integrate with a wide range of tools and platforms.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] Runners are the agents that run your jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] These agents can run on physical machines or virtual instances.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] In your `.gitlab-ci.yml` file, you can specify a container image you want to use when running the job.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] The runner loads the image, clones your project, and runs the job either locally or in the container.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] If you use GitLab.com, runners on Linux, Windows, and macOS are already available for use.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] If needed, you can also register your own runners.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] GitLab CI/CD variables are key-value pairs you use to store and pass configuration settings and sensitive information, like passwords or API keys, to jobs in a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] GitLab CI/CD expressions allow you to inject data dynamically into your pipeline configuration.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] The data available depends on the expression context.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] For example, the `inputs` context allows you to access information passed into the configuration file from a parent file or when a pipeline is run.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] Use CI/CD variables to customize jobs by making values defined elsewhere accessible to jobs.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] You can hard-code CI/CD variables in your `.gitlab-ci.yml` file, set them in your project settings, or generate them dynamically.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] You can define them for the project, group, or instance.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] CI/CD expressions use the `$[[ ]]` syntax and are validated when you create a pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] You can also validate expressions in the pipeline editor before committing changes.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] A CI/CD component is a reusable pipeline configuration unit.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] Use a CI/CD component to compose an entire pipeline configuration or a small part of a larger pipeline.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] You can add a component to your pipeline configuration with `include:component`.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] Reusable components help reduce duplication, improve maintainability, and promote consistency across projects.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] Create a component project and publish it to the CI/CD Catalog to share your component across multiple projects.
[src:gitlab-ci/ee-ci] GitLab also has CI/CD component templates for common tasks and integrations.
[src:gitlab-ci/gitlab] GitLab was created in 2011 by Ukrainian programmer Dmytro Zaporozhets.
[src:gitlab-ci/gitlab] It was a side project, written in Ruby on Rails.
[src:gitlab-ci/gitlab] The company was formerly known as GitLab B.V.
[src:gitlab-ci/gitlab] In July 2015, the name changed to GitLab Inc.
[src:gitlab-ci/gitlab] In 2021, it became a publicly traded company on the Nasdaq Global Select Market, under the ticker symbol GTLB.
[src:gitlab-ci/gitlab] In 2024, co-founder and CEO Sid Sijbrandij stepped down to focus on cancer treatment, with Bill Staples succeeding him as CEO while Sijbrandij remained as board chairman.
